< Review>
A pleasant surprise for someone who is not a fan of this type food. Invited to join friends. First timer so my expectations were low. Expected to enjoy the company but not the cusine.
Food was tasty and very enjoyable. Great servers. Biggest surprise? The food served in the bowl remained steaming hot for the entirety of my meal, which is a big deal, as I'm a very slow eater and the downside to eating slow is the food gets cold before finishing. Good job Mapo!< /Review>

< rate>
3</rate>
< review>
It is pretty pricey based on the not-so-much portion. The pork cheek was the better ones, and the short rib was quite lean, and could use a bit more slices with its 42$ price tag. I am not too sure if it was really short rib because it was just not to good.

All other small dishes were so-so, but the grill itself was nicely heated gas-powered cast iron. The place was not loud at all compared to other similar style Korean barbecue.

Service was okay, and I could see this place doing a lot better if they address some of the issues.</review>

<Review>The ribs. The St.Louis ribs were amazing! Granted that each of us has our own likes, dislikes, and preferences about food, these were some of the best ribs I've ever had - so tender and dreamily easy to coax off the bone ... and the sauce (homemade by chef) was like a sensational peppery kiss. Another family member ordered the dunganess crab, dayboat scallop and shrimp cakes with sriracha lime sauce (not very spicy) - he loved it. DO NOT come here for a good meal. We had the chicken sandwich. Kid had a cheeseburger. Also had the black ravioli and another Italian based dish. The ravioli and other Italian dishes tasted bland with an strong tomato sauce flavor to give you your dose of Italian. The burger was bland and very dry (the ones I make at home are better). The chicken sandwich was bland as well. It was fried in decent batter that lacked flavor and the bun further took away from the potential it had at being good. My brother and wife didn‚Äôt even touch their chicken sandwich after having a bite of mine and not liking it. My brother told our waitress that the meal was not good at all. Even though it was apparent that the other chicken sandwich meal wasn‚Äôt even touched there wasn‚Äôt any gesture towards mediating/accommodating the bad experience with the meal. After working at some renowned restaurants, some of these things just seem like common sense to me but I guess they are not. Will not be returning and will discourage others from doing so unless they just want to go drink somewhere.</Text>

<Text>Came here on a weeknight with a reservation but probably didn't need one because it wasn't super busy.

My friend & I started with the pork belly which was really good. Super rich but melted in your mouth like butter.

They didn't have a bourbon menu, our waitress said they were working on it, but she recommended a whiskey she liked which ended up being delicious.

For our main course we both had the steak & frites (comes with bone marrow). I had mine rare and my friend had it medium rare. I didn't see too much of a difference between the way it was cooked but it leaned more toward the rare side which I didn't mind. The steak was fantastic, cooked & seasoned to perfection. The bone marrow was great, I dipped my fries in it.

Over all we had a great experience. The food was great, the price wasn't crazy and the service was very friendly and knowledgeable. I definitely recommend this place and will come back. :)</Text></record></dataset><record>

<Date>1468298971411<//Date>< text>
The food at Bourbon and Beef is underwhelming, especially for the price, and the lackluster service doesn't do much to salvage the situation; I won't be going back.

We got a table right away on a not very busy Monday, placed our order, and then waited 30 minutes for soup and a salad to arrive. The server apologetically informed us that their computer crashed and the kitchen never got the order, but it shouldn't take 30 minutes for a server to realize there's a problem, especially when nearby tables that were seated after us were already getting food. Once the food arrived the mixed green salad and french onion soup were fine, but everything else was subpar. The burger was laughably tall, and even if it had been short enough to take a bite it fell apart instantly. The ravioli was fairly bland for $5 a piece, and the fingerling potatoes weren't the least bit crispy.

Overall, Bourbon and Beef was a waste of time and money, and almost anywhere else along College would be a better choice.</text>

< text>
Made a reservation for 11:30 which I glad I made because this place was getting full. We started off with a couple of Morning Margaritas and ordered the steak and eggs and duck and waffles.

I wondered why they would call it a Morning Margarita then I took a sip. It was a strong punch of alcohol and bitterness from whatever citrus they added, probably lime; for $11 each it was worth it. Our food came and I have to say I had one of the best steaks of my life. With the steak and eggs came with potatoes and this sauce. The steak by itself was tender, seasoned very well, and the fat attached on the side really heightened the flavor all together. I guess that happens when it‚Äôs grass-fed steak. The potatoes where cooked as perfectly as the steak, crispy on the outside and soft in the inside. Eggs were eggs and really there wasn't anything distinct.

I tried the duck from the duck and waffles and I have to say as someone who avoids duck because of the fear of tasting the gamy taste of duck this duck did not have it what-so-ever. It was delicious with the combination of the egg yolk and syrup. It did come with an orange jam which was very sweet and he used a little. For each entr√©e pricing at $17 (duck) and $20 (steak) so for the quality and taste of it, it was worth it.

Everything was going very well until I noticed a couple of the waitresses and a chef, the head maybe, where heavily discussing something because the looks on everyone‚Äôs faces did not look calm. We then had this waitress, not the one serving our table, to tell us to basically hurry up our meal. It went along the lines of ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt want to rush your meal but there‚Äôs a group who made a reservation that has been waiting for 45 minutes‚Äù I can tell you we were not eating for that was probably the total time of us being seated, ordering, waiting for our order, and eating. She then stated she can move us to another table and then reiterated to take our time but HURRY UP. I then asked if she can give us 5 more minutes, we were almost done. She said yes however the people who reserved have been waiting for a while.

You can figure out a better way to approach your patrons with this dilemma by simply coming in calmly but we decided to take the option, the ONLY option, of being moved to another table and finishing up our meal. The other table wasn‚Äôt even ready. . . REALLY?! So she basically threw the plate on the table and rushed away. My date was approached by the chef during this transition and was told his meal would be comped. My thought why not my meal as well? At this point I did not want this to ruin a really nice date.

Oh, even putting that aside it really was sad and annoying to deal with the check because after the fact the chef told my date he would comp him we were charged for his plate. So basically there was no communication between the chef and the waitresses who basically almost forgot about us. Glad though the waitress took the meal off when I mentioned to her about what was told.

Even though our first waitress was nice, this waitress [who is blonde, putting it out there] was rude,  didn‚Äôt work well under pressure, and not at least bit professional. Even though she gave us another table it felt as though it was a swept-under-the-rug scenario and there was no form of sincere apology. It was very, ‚Äúsorry, sorry, sorry, I need to seat this party‚Äù

Usually with bad service I would come back to give it another chance. After having the service I had at Bourbon and Beef I wouldn‚Äôt want to come back. It left that kind of impression on me.</text>

< review>
Best Persian Barbary in town. You can taste the difference between the fake Barbary from Sabzi market and the genuine Barbary from Vanak. My wife also likes their kabob. They give to skewers of fat kabob and tomatoe and salad.

The owner and his son are very cordial.

The only problem I have with this place is the fact that the have a B from the Health Department. I am hoping that Mr. Vanak can read this post and bring his grade up to an A.</review>

< Review>
We've been taking our dogs to Midland for more than a decade and we have never been disappointed. While wait times have increased a bit, we have to remember that we're in a pandemic and they're doing the best they can to care for both our pets and their employees.

The Covid-19 precautions that the clinic is taking is pretty standard; you arrive, call in to check in, and then wait for a tech to come collect your doggo. We have never waited longer than five minutes. Once the doctor has had a look, they call you and you can have a discussion with them. The doctors are top notch - they know their stuff and they know how to explain it in a way that helps you understand what's going on with your fur (or feather) baby. And, as an added bonus, all of the vets have the ability to put you at ease. They definitely want to make sure your pet is happy and healthy.

We always recommend Midland to anyone who has a new pet or wants a new vet.< /Review>

We had an emergency with our 13 yr old dog with Congestive heart disease. They made an appointment for him at 3:30 that day but said I could bring him in earlier to get him on oxygen if he was having difficulty breathing. I brought him in 2 hours early and they took him in fairly quickly, considering the whole social distancing thing and having to wait in numbered parking spaces for the Vet Techs to come get your pet. Within about 30 mins Dr.Switzer called me and very thoroughly explained his findings and what he did. He gave us hope that our dog is not in end stage of CHF and no need to consider euthanasia at this time. We brought him home and within and hour and a half he was eating and drinking again and has improved every day since. Dr. Switzer called later that afternoon to check on him and to give us additional advice to make him comfortable and what signs to look for should he need to be seen again. I was very impressed with the attention to details and level of care. Thank you Midland Animal Clinic.< /text>

<Name>Rory Berry Bishop< /Name><Date>1393268486413</Date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
I chose this clinic because of its proximity to my home and work.  I have two dogs, one senior & one just past the puppy stage.  I love the 'new' facilify - clean, spacious, lots of room for waiting clientele to spread out, beautiful all the way around - and it seems that the initial phase of 'this place only wants more money because of their new facility/rude reception staff' is over.  I confess, I waited a couple of years because I suspected this might occur....

So - I like that the vets/staff support me in my care of my dogs.  They didn't try to dissuade me from making my dogs' food, but checked my recipe so I'm guessing they'd tell me if it weren't meeting the dogs' needs.  They really seem to want to help me take care of my dogs the way I'd like to care for them.  It would take several paragraphs to give examples, but I urge you to just tell them how you feel and what you are doing/want to do, because in my experience I didn't encounter the, 'use this dog food/treatment/product' attitude.

I see that another reviewer found he had to go in to their office to pick up a prescription for use for online Rx purchase, so I'll make sure I don't expect them to fax it if asked.  This doesn't happen to be a big deal to me, as I live within a mile of the facility. If I run into trouble with prescriptions, I'll have to downgrade to 4 stars.

Overall, a great experience, upon which I am planning to build.< /text>

<Text>I have had nothing but good experiences at this practice.  Dr Augustine diagnosed a serious condition with one of my cats and has controlled it for her.  I have never been turned away when I needed an appointment at short notice.  I have never had to wait more than 5-6 minutes.  They do not try to up-sell high-priced treatments and make pet owners feel guilty about it.  Several of my friends have switched to Midland and have great faith in the treatment their pets have had.  Thank you to everyone there.

I respectfully submit to those who are unhappy with this clinic that they check prices elsewhere.  Midland is comparable.  Furthermore, if you wish to see the same vet every time, you can request the same vet.  Also, all vets anesthetize cats for teeth cleaning.  It is not cheap to get this done.  It is also not required.  The decision is yours.  It is good medical advice to be offered the options.

Midland is very popular, always busy, and being put on hold is to be expected in such a practice.  A short wait is worth it to me to ensure my 5 cats and 1 dog get good, caring treatment.<//Text><resp>None</resp><user_id>115202983633113422664< /user_id>< Rating>

< Text>
I regularly travel to the Poway area with my dog to visit and assist elderly relatives. As a precaution I inquire from others I encounter walking their dogs which vets are good and each time Midland was recommended. So when my dog who's stitches from a minor surgery weren't healing I took him to Midland Animal Clinic. I was able to get a same day appointment, the staff was professional, courteous and efficient. The vet we saw, an older gentleman was courteous and informative. He spent time to evaluate my dog completely and did not rush our visit being efficient and thorough. Eventhough, we were just visiting from out of town we were treated the same as if they were our primary vet at home. The cost of the visit was reasonable.  On another visit to the area, we returned to have a stubborn tick removed and were able to get an immediate appointment. The fee was nominal.  We have been very pleased with the care we received at Midland and if we move back to San Diego would definitely be regular clients.<//Text>

<review>Have now used them for just over a year.  Clean place, very nice people.  My only complaint is that I can not get the vet to fax a prescription to an internet store like 1-800-PETMEDS.  Its against their policy.  I had to go in and pick up the prescription and then send it in.  Our previous vet before we moved to San Diego had no problem faxing the prescription.

Now on to some of the comments that I have seen.  Yes, there are multiple vets so you may not get the same one.  However, if there is a vet that you like you should be able to find out when they are on and get them.  Do they take your pet from the room for shots and weigh-in.  Yup, but my Gus had no issue with that.  If that is an issue with you then bring it up with them first, not after the fact.  Personally I think the prices are reasonable.  Both the Vet and the vet assistant spend a long time with you and your pet so that is nice.  It never seems like you are rushed.

Back to the faxing of prescriptions.  When I request the refill they did not tell me initially that it was against policy. When I came back from vacation and no meds that is when I found out it was against their policy.  So there was a communication issue with that.

So the 4 star rating is because they refuse to fax prescriptions.<//review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None<//response><gmapID>0x80dbfa5e5c53acd9:0x60ff657c57c5178e<//gmapID></record>

< Text>
I have been going here for 7 years and love, love, love Dr. Davis! She is engaged and has such a passion which shows through and through. I have big dogs and she doesn't hesitate to get on the ground and stay with them the entire exam. She understands my needs, listens and answers every question as they come up. She doesn't recommend needless tests and is mindful of costs. I completely trust her with my pups!

When one of my pups developed epilepsy at a senior age, the clinic treated her with love and compassion. When an episode became too difficult for them to handle, they did not hesitate to recommend us to a speciality as they knew she would be in better hands. I cannot thank them enough for doing all they could for Smuckers during her final days.

The clinic is open and friendly. There is a huge waiting room so pets can be spread out and not interact with each other if they don't wish to. I love the message board and always feel relaxed. Both the waiting area and the exam rooms are very clean and odor free.

The techs that assist the vets are wonderful, caring and very thorough with any follow up questions. Front desk staff are efficient and good-natured, for the most part. Sometimes they appear no nonsense but I understand they are juggling lots of things behind that desk - checking in, checking out, scheduling, fielding phone calls, etc.

They are a bit on the high side for an office visit but my pups are worth it, especially since the breed I own are suspectible to cancers and joint problems.

I highly recommend Midland Animal Clinic - I can't imagine going anywhere else!

BTW, I read other posts about seeing different vets on visits. I did this until I got lucky with Dr. Davis. Once she saw my pups, she became "my vet." :-) I ask for her by name, so if you like a particular vet - just ask to schedule your appointment with them!</Text>

Will never go back or recomend anyone i know go back here.</text>

--

Update: I've been working with Wes at QShark who has been very responsive in helping to resolve the situation. As we unpack we'll be in contact with them on the damages, and they will be refunding us a large portion of the initial cost.

---

I struggle to put into words how truly terrible our experience was. But I'll try‚Äîunprofessional, damaging and heartbreaking. I do not wish it upon any one. It took me just over two weeks to even write this review, because every time I think about it it makes me so upset.

*Here are the low lights*:

They advertise that they will come prepared with boxes to help you pack, and all you need to do is pay for the boxes you use. This is not true‚Äîthey do not come with boxes for purchase and they were clearly not interested in helping pack.

When they arrived and saw we still had some things which needed packing, they asked who was going to do it... I reminded them that that's why we hired them. They said "ok, all good. It's fine".

The only boxes they had come prepared with were MASSIVE (probably around 5 feet tall) wardrobe boxes. All we had left in the house to pack were things from the kitchen (glasses, plates, etc.) and other smaller items (ex: table lamps, audio equipment). Sometimes they placed our items in these massive boxes carefully, but often it felt like our stuff was just swimming inside the boxes, banging against one another.

I communicated to the lead mover, Robert, that we were going to be putting everything into storage in our new home since the house was not yet move in ready. So, I asked if we could keep things like the moving blankets on our designer furniture. He said I'd have to pay for them‚Äî$15 each. I said, no problem, I will pay for the blankets and the boxes.

As they were unpacking the belongings into the storage at our new house, we noticed they started unpacking the massive wardrobe boxes they had brought. We alerted them that since it's going into storage, to please not unpack them, and I restated I'd buy the boxes. Robert replied, "No, these are *my* boxes". Not only was everything clanking around inside during transport because they were too big, but they weren't available for me to buy as was advertised.

The same thing then also happened with our DWR furniture which I thought would be inside of the moving blankets. They unpacked them, and now there are scratches all over.

When unpacking, they cantilevered chairs on top of chairs next to delicate items. They placed a table on top of the couch, with stacks of boxes on top of it. All of our belongings precariously stored.

Since we weren't allowed to keep the boxes, many items are just sitting around, completely unpacked. We've already noticed some items are damaged, and I am scared to think what our fragile items and family heirlooms will be like... We bought a mattress cover for the mattress since it'd be inside in the construction area, and once I left, I realized they had removed the cover. So the mattress is now filthy from construction dust.

When they were done, he tried to get me to sign a customer satisfaction document. I felt extremely uncomfortable and pressured and intimidated by him to sign. I told him I was unhappy with the way things turned out, and he reminded me that they are professionals. I signed the first line, and then immediately crossed out my signature and wrote that I was unhappy and refused the sign the rest. He stormed out angrily.

*Positives*:
The crew under Robert were nice guys. They certainly intended well, but given the poor leadership, it was clear there was no quality bar they felt they needed to meet.< /Text>< pictures>

105108321820066729204<//UserId.>
<username>Shelbie hoddle</username><Date>1590378539524</Date><rate>5<//rate>< Text>
We decided during quarantine, that this would be a great time to move. I went through Thumbtack and carefully read through tons of companies and reviews, and I stumbled across QShark. Their pricing was comparable to other companies, but the reviews were superior to all others. A week or so prior to our move date, I went ahead and booked with them. They confirmed everything over the phone and via email as well. The Called the night prior to our move go confirm everything. They didn't charge us any differently for a Sunday during memorial day weekend either, which really surprised me. The morning of, they called me an hour and a half prior to our start time, letting us know they'd be arriving at approximately 10:45am for our 11am time slot.

I met them downstairs as they wore masks for social distancing, Anthony and Eugene were our mover helpers! They filled out the start time as 10:55am and got to work right away.

They graciously worked with us and all of our things. I explained that since it was a short move(5 miles), I didn't need everything wrapped, just the dressers, fridge, tv stand and Rocking chair. They happily obliged. They worked at an even pace start to finish. They followed behind us at our new place, and due to spacing, they couldn't quite fit through the driveway. They made the trips back and forth getting all of our furniture in our new home.

I want to stop right here and say this: Never once did these guys complain about a single thing. They were the nicest, kindest people we could have asked for in this move. Moving can be stressful, but these guys took that all out of the equation.

Anyways, back to moving in. They were so quick to offer to jump in any time I maybe wanted to rearrange something because it fit a little better over there. They even took our couch apart and door off the hinge so our couch could fit in a certain room.

They out everything exactly where I asked them to. They treated myself and my husband with so much respect. These guys are honestly the only people I would allow to help me move again. They listened to me, heard what I asked, and did it joyfully. They're hard workers and I never saw them stop for anything.

Total cost: $428 for 4 Hours, 15 minutes for a Sunday rate of $89/hour and the $50 fuel fee.

As this was a long drive to our initial location, there was a $50 fuel fee but this was discussed prior to my booking their services.

I had NO last minute additional costs. They didn't add a single thing to our move or try to be sneaky at the end.

They're genuinely nice, hard working guys and I'd be happy to have them back next time, and to recommend them to anyone else moving.</Text>

< review>
These guys are the best!  I spoke with Vlad on the phone.  He was very nice, giving me the information I needed without being pushy at all. When I said I needed confirm the reservation with my husband, he just told me to call back when it was convenient.  My husband and I agreed that Qshark would be the best moving company for us to use.  All other companies that we talked with were very vague about details and wanted to provide too many movers with too large a truck for what needed to be moved.  The other companies seemed to have a lot of hidden charges and their estimates were at least double of what Vlad thought the move would cost.  My husband said that the movers, Kelly and Ken, were hard workers and fast.  They were careful when moving the furniture but moved quickly.  My husband was very impressed by how professional Kelly and Ken were. Qsharks is up front and honest.  There were no hidden charges and the move was amazingly easy and very reasonable.  There is no doubt that Qsharks is the one to turn to for a move. We will definitely be calling them for any other moves in our future.</review>

My husband and I had managed to previously move our entire apartment from one 3rd-floor apartment to this old 3rd-floor apartment in about 3/4 hours including driving time.
This job that Qshark gave us took 7 hours.
I was floored- they arrived at 2pm and left around 9/9:30pm. Some things were badly scuffed- others were pristine (I believe a lot of the extra time was from over-protecting some items). When the two gentlemen entered the apartment they said "this shouldn't take long you don't have a lot of stuff" - it's an 800 sq. ft apartment, so absolutely we didn't have much.
By 8pm I asked how much longer, I was told about 30 minutes. Took another hour-ish. It being a three-story town-home, things weren't put on the floor they needed to be (bed and couches were fine, desks and drawers were not). I gave up and told them to just put all the boxes in the living room so I could move them up or down depending on where they needed to go- I couldn't afford the additional time it would take them!
They were obviously fairly tired when they arrived, and I can only imagine the extra stories really sucked when already tired, but this is their job and I was floored at how long it took. I kept asking if I could help- and was told no it's fine.
They were pretty nice in person, decent people, but from being tired and this job taking twice as long as I had really thought it would take, It was insane.
It taking twice as long as I had assumed (if one bedroom took 7 hours, imagine a two or three!) I asked for the price, basically $600. Well I definitely don't have that lying around in bills while moving- so I offered a check (as a business owner I accept checks on a daily basis) and was promptly told they don't accept those- but if I had my debit card they would happily charge me the higher rate. Ha! No! They got their manager on the phone, I explained the length, the cost, the issues, and they took an hour off of the time- which I do appreciate- and OK'd the check as long as they took a photo of my ID, as they have "had issues in the past" with checks.
They did the job, they moved my stuff, but I honestly should have just paid some family friends to do the job and it would have gotten done faster and probably with less hassle / scuffed items.
Then to top it all off- I find out this morning that our TV power cable was accidentally kept by one of the movers. I reached out to one of the movers who had texted me and tried to arrange a time to get it dropped off- which i was then cancelled on last minute. I offered to swing by after work, which they had suggested was a potential solution, and they stopped responding (around noon today). < Text>
Hello so today I went to Northgate market. My experience was not great!! The carts are not inside. You need to come back out to get a cart. They have a person on the entrance giving you a  towel. But you have to ask for it. So shouldn't it be that carts should be inside already sanitized.  At least all other markets do have it like that! So moving on forward. I get in line to pay. I wait my turn so the person that is getting ready to pay, move forward. Then she leaves, and the cashier leaves too. So my husband, and I are looking for her. Not knowing if we should put our groceries in the bannister , or what. So as were about to go to another checkout. She comes back and says nothing. So we asked her if she was open. She says yes.
